re stigmatized as lower class, sexually loose women with too much independence. George's absorbing story of how these women and men negotiate this complicated network provides a groundbreaking perspective on the shifting interactions of two nations and two cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEast IndiansxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aEast IndianszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMan-woman relationshipszIndia. 0aMan-woman relationshipszUnited States. 0aNurseszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 0aTransnationalism. 0aWomen foreign workersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomen immigrantsxEmploymentxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomenxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen, East IndianxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aWomen, East IndianzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aamerican success story.  achurch roles.  aclass issues.  across cultural.  aeconomic mobility.  aemigration and immigration.  agender issues.  agender relations.  agender studies.  aimmigrant communities.  aimmigrant experiences.  aimmigrant women.  aimmigration patterns.  aindia.  anonfiction.  anurses.  aprofessional women.  arace and class.  asending communities.  asocial networks.  asocial status.  atextbooks.  atransnational migration.  aunited states.  awomens history.  aworking women.1 aBurawoy, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093835940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938359423Coveruhttp